## Core mental model (always true)

- **Declarative build model.** You describe *what* the project is (coordinates, dependencies, plugins),
  not imperative build steps. Both tools apply **conventions over configuration** — a standard layout
  (`src/main/java`, `src/test/java`) means little config for a normal project.
- **Maven = fixed lifecycle of phases.** A *lifecycle* is an ordered list of *phases*
  (`validate → compile → test → package → verify → install → deploy`); plugin *goals* bind to phases.
  Running a phase runs every earlier phase too — `mvn package` compiles and tests first.
- **Gradle = a directed acyclic task graph.** Tasks declare inputs/outputs and dependencies on other
  tasks; Gradle computes the order and skips tasks whose inputs are unchanged (incremental + cache).
  `./gradlew build` runs `assemble` + `check`.
- **Coordinates are `groupId:artifactId:version` (GAV).** Same identity model in both tools; the GAV
  addresses an artifact in a repository (Maven Central by default).
- **Transitive dependencies** are pulled in automatically; the tool **resolves** a single version per
  module from the whole graph (the algorithms differ — see deps-ci.md). This is where conflicts live.
- **The wrapper pins the build-tool version** so every machine and CI runs the identical build. Always
  invoke `./mvnw` / `./gradlew`, not a globally installed `mvn`/`gradle`.

## Headline gotchas / common mistakes

- **Version conflicts ("dependency hell").** Two transitive paths want different versions of the same
  GAV; the tool silently picks one and you get `NoSuchMethodError`/`LinkageError` at runtime. Inspect
  the tree and pin via `dependencyManagement`/`platform` (deps-ci.md) rather than guessing.
- **Scope vs configuration mismatch.** Putting a runtime-only driver on `compile`/`implementation`, or a
  test lib on the main classpath, leaks the wrong artifacts. Match scope (Maven) / configuration
  (Gradle) to actual usage — `runtimeOnly` ≠ `implementation`, `provided` ≠ `compileOnly`.
- **Forgetting the wrapper.** Running a globally installed `mvn`/`gradle` of a different version gives
  "works on my machine" build drift. Commit the wrapper and use it everywhere.
- **SNAPSHOT vs release.** `-SNAPSHOT` versions are mutable and re-resolved; a build that passed
  yesterday can break today. Release builds must depend only on fixed (non-SNAPSHOT) versions.
- **Tests silently skipped.** `-DskipTests` (compiles but skips execution) and `-Dmaven.test.skip=true`
  (skips compile *and* run) hide failures; Gradle `-x test` does the same. Don't ship green builds that
  never ran the suite.
- **Gradle daemon / cache staleness.** A stale daemon or build cache can serve old outputs. When results
  look impossible, try `--no-daemon`, `--rerun-tasks`, or stop daemons (`./gradlew --stop`).
- **Plugin vs dependency confusion.** A *plugin* extends the build (adds tasks/goals); a *dependency*
  is code your app compiles/runs against. They are declared in different places — don't put a plugin in
  `<dependencies>`/`dependencies {}` or a library in `<build><plugins>`/`plugins {}`.

## Live docs protocol

For version-sensitive or uncovered details (exact goals, task names, plugin coordinates, DSL):

1. **context7 MCP** (best for goal/task/config names). Resolve and query both libraries; if the tools
   aren't loaded, load them via ToolSearch
   (`select:mcp__plugin_context7_context7__resolve-library-id`,
   `select:mcp__plugin_context7_context7__query-docs`):
   - **Maven** — `/apache/maven-site` (guides, POM reference) and `/apache/maven` (core).
   - **Gradle** — `/websites/gradle_current_userguide` (the user guide).
   Pin to the repo's installed version when context7 offers versioned IDs.
2. **WebFetch** the canonical docs: Maven guides at `https://maven.apache.org/guides/` and the Gradle
   user guide at `https://docs.gradle.org/current/userguide/userguide.html`.
3. Cross-check plugin coordinates against the plugin's own page (e.g. the Spring Boot build plugin
   reference) before pasting them.

Say when an answer is **verified-from-docs** vs **baked-in knowledge**. Always adapt to the project's
actual Maven/Gradle and Java versions; if they differ from your defaults, state what changes.
